  "prompt": "Are all caterpillars butterflies?",
  "response": "No, not all caterpillars become butterflies. Caterpillars are the larval stage of insects in the order Lepidoptera, which includes both **butterflies** and **moths**. While all butterfly species begin as caterpillars, many caterpillars belong to moth species instead. The distinction lies in the specific species and its life cycle. For example:\n\n- **Butterflies** develop from caterpillars that eventually form a chrysalis (pupa) before emerging as adults.  \n- **Moths** also start as caterpillars but often spin a cocoon (instead of a chrysalis) for their pupal stage.  \n\nThus, while all butterflies were once caterpillars, not all caterpillars become butterflies\u2014many become moths.",
